  <div id = group4>
      <p>
          Butterflies belong to the order Lepidoptera, 
          which belongs to the class of insects 
          in the arthropod branch of the animal kingdom. 
          Moths are also included in this group. 
          There are around 20.000 butterfly species. 
          They can be observed all over the world except Antarctica. 
          The word Lepidoptera means scaly wings in Greek. 
          If you look very carefully, 
          you can see these scaly shapes on the wings of butterflies; 
          these are hairs with flattened and enlarged tips. 
          Like all other insects, butterflies have six legs, 
          a main body in three parts (head, thorax (centre) and abdomen (tail end)), 
          two antennae and two honeycomb eyes.
      </p>
