      <div class = p1>
          Metamorphosis begins when female butterflies lay their 
          pinhead-sized eggs on a leaf. 
          They lay them on the leaf because the leaves 
          are a source of food for the caterpillars.
      </div>

      <div class = p2>
          The egg period lasts a few days and 
          caterpillars hatch from the broken eggs. 
          During this period, which lasts about two weeks, 
          the caterpillars molt four or five times.

      </div>    

      <div class = p3>
          During the pupation period, 
          the caterpillar hangs itself upside down on a leaf and 
          forms a cocoon and stays in this cocoon for about a week. 
          Depending on the species, 
          this process can last for more than a year, 
          because some butterfly species hibernate as pupae. 
      </div>

      <div class = p4>
          The butterfly emerges from the cocoon, 
          pumps blood into its wings and starts flying 
          within an hour or two after drying out.
      
      </p>            
